WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:07.530 --> 00:00:09.610
MALE SPEAKER: So
I actually think

00:00:09.610 --> 00:00:13.000
I'd like to start first with a
question about Racepoint, which

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:15.180
you started in 2002.

00:00:15.180 --> 00:00:20.470
And actually, I'll start
with another question.

00:00:20.470 --> 00:00:23.400
Why did you decide
to write books?

00:00:23.400 --> 00:00:26.395
And who are you writing for?

00:00:26.395 --> 00:00:28.020
LARRY WEBER: The
first book that nobody

00:00:28.020 --> 00:00:32.420
read, I wanted to write
about all the new technology

00:00:32.420 --> 00:00:36.640
leaders I had been working with,
like Steve Jobs, Larry Ellison.

00:00:36.640 --> 00:00:40.360
I had met Sergey and Larry,
but it was a little later.

00:00:40.360 --> 00:00:43.800
It was like 2002 in Aspen.

00:00:43.800 --> 00:00:47.900
But I was amazed
that these guys were

00:00:47.900 --> 00:00:50.620
different than the corporate
leaders I had worked with,

00:00:50.620 --> 00:00:53.690
and so I was just
observing the way they

00:00:53.690 --> 00:00:54.770
were building companies.

00:00:54.770 --> 00:00:56.530
And it was called
"The Provocateurs."

00:00:56.530 --> 00:00:59.820
How a new generation of leaders
are building communities, not

00:00:59.820 --> 00:01:01.010
just companies.

00:01:01.010 --> 00:01:04.180
So it was that sort of angle,
and it was the late '90s.

00:01:04.180 --> 00:01:07.130
And I just wanted to capture
all these people that I had met

00:01:07.130 --> 00:01:07.770
and do that.

00:01:07.770 --> 00:01:12.000
And then, I started realizing--
and this relates to Racepoint.

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:13.460
By the way, I
couldn't use my name.

00:01:13.460 --> 00:01:17.640
My lawyer didn't tell me I
had sold my name to IPG too.

00:01:17.640 --> 00:01:20.330
So that's why it's called
Racepoint Global, which

00:01:20.330 --> 00:01:22.750
is after one of the oldest
lighthouses in America

00:01:22.750 --> 00:01:23.495
off Provincetown.

00:01:26.130 --> 00:01:30.130
But anyway, the
other books started

00:01:30.130 --> 00:01:32.770
to seep in because I realized
technology obviously was going

00:01:32.770 --> 00:01:34.690
to change marketing forever.

00:01:34.690 --> 00:01:37.920
And it was the last category
that didn't even have an ERP

00:01:37.920 --> 00:01:39.990
system, or enterprise system.

00:01:39.990 --> 00:01:45.620
And then, I was also an early
stupid investor in Friendster,

00:01:45.620 --> 00:01:48.380
and I knew that the
impact of social media

00:01:48.380 --> 00:01:49.810
was going to be huge.

00:01:49.810 --> 00:01:54.240
So I wanted to
write to marketers.

00:01:54.240 --> 00:01:56.180
There wasn't CMO titles then.

00:01:56.180 --> 00:01:59.040
But I wanted to write to
marketers and CEOs-- so

00:01:59.040 --> 00:02:02.030
C-levels-- about the
coming vast changes

00:02:02.030 --> 00:02:03.820
in reaching your customers.

00:02:03.820 --> 00:02:06.870
And I thought social media
was the first huge computing

00:02:06.870 --> 00:02:11.230
wave after HTML that was
going to have huge impact.

00:02:11.230 --> 00:02:13.210
And so I wrote a
book that became

00:02:13.210 --> 00:02:16.970
my biggest bestseller in 2006
called "Marketing to the Social

00:02:16.970 --> 00:02:17.500
Web."

00:02:17.500 --> 00:02:19.264
And it wasn't because
it was a great book.

00:02:19.264 --> 00:02:21.430
I think it was because it
was the first book written

00:02:21.430 --> 00:02:22.526
on that topic.

00:02:22.526 --> 00:02:23.900
And then I also
learned something

00:02:23.900 --> 00:02:27.470
about publishing, which
is that if you write

00:02:27.470 --> 00:02:29.500
a more instructive
book and it's pretty

00:02:29.500 --> 00:02:31.697
decent about a new
topic, all of a sudden

00:02:31.697 --> 00:02:33.530
it's in the curriculum
of a bunch of schools

00:02:33.530 --> 00:02:37.310
because we were trying to figure
out why the book would sell

00:02:37.310 --> 00:02:40.340
so much in August and January.

00:02:40.340 --> 00:02:42.310
And then we realized
it was everywhere

00:02:42.310 --> 00:02:45.060
from Birmingham at the
University of Alabama

00:02:45.060 --> 00:02:47.750
to Columbia.

00:02:47.750 --> 00:02:50.090
And then, my favorite
book, the third book

00:02:50.090 --> 00:02:53.860
I wrote in 2009, which had
a telling chapter in it,

00:02:53.860 --> 00:02:57.090
which is one of the best books
I've ever written that nobody

00:02:57.090 --> 00:03:00.430
read called "Sticks and Stones
about Digital Reputation"

00:03:00.430 --> 00:03:01.920
in 2009.

00:03:01.920 --> 00:03:06.720
And I had a chapter that
Harvard Business Review loved

00:03:06.720 --> 00:03:09.350
called the YouTube Juggernaut.

00:03:09.350 --> 00:03:12.000
And this was seven,
eight years ago.

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:14.650
I was thinking about
after I met Chad Hurley.

00:03:14.650 --> 00:03:17.210
And even though he
was just having fun,

00:03:17.210 --> 00:03:21.610
I saw a future where most
data and most content

00:03:21.610 --> 00:03:23.730
was going to be
presented visually.

00:03:23.730 --> 00:03:26.290
And that there would probably
more of a category of data

00:03:26.290 --> 00:03:29.520
called visual information
versus just videography.

00:03:29.520 --> 00:03:32.006
And I was playing
around with that idea,

00:03:32.006 --> 00:03:33.630
so I thought that
would be a cool thing

00:03:33.630 --> 00:03:35.760
to write about so I did that.

00:03:35.760 --> 00:03:39.440
And this is a long answer
to a simple question.

00:03:39.440 --> 00:03:42.650
I also figured out how to
write a book within six

00:03:42.650 --> 00:03:43.920
to nine months.

00:03:43.920 --> 00:03:47.590
You know, how to research
it, write it, have a helper.

00:03:47.590 --> 00:03:50.670
I had two MBA
students do research,

00:03:50.670 --> 00:03:52.810
then I had a ghost
writer who I'd finally

00:03:52.810 --> 00:03:58.310
have given her credit so I'm
not a complete sexist ass.

00:03:58.310 --> 00:04:00.930
Who would say, Larry,
you wrote that last week.

00:04:00.930 --> 00:04:03.840
That's not another
chapter kind of thing.

00:04:03.840 --> 00:04:09.300
And then, I drifted to a
bigger topic, which did OK,

00:04:09.300 --> 00:04:10.850
the book before this one.

00:04:10.850 --> 00:04:12.880
This is a bestseller
now, but that one

00:04:12.880 --> 00:04:14.690
was called "Everywhere,"
and it was my view

00:04:14.690 --> 00:04:18.100
that social media was not
just impacting marketing.

00:04:18.100 --> 00:04:20.130
It was impacting
the way we did HR.

00:04:20.130 --> 00:04:22.110
It was impacting the
way we did finance.

00:04:22.110 --> 00:04:24.040
It was impacting the
way we did sales.

00:04:24.040 --> 00:04:27.210
So in "Everywhere," I was
trying to take a different,

00:04:27.210 --> 00:04:29.030
and I think that
was a little early.

00:04:29.030 --> 00:04:30.860
And this one seems
just about right,

00:04:30.860 --> 00:04:32.850
and this one has its roots.

00:04:32.850 --> 00:04:34.550
It's called "The
Digital Marketer-- 10

00:04:34.550 --> 00:04:38.352
New Skills you Need to Know
to Stay Customer Centric."

00:04:38.352 --> 00:04:40.310
It's about what I think
is today and the future

00:04:40.310 --> 00:04:43.310
of marketing, which is
what "Racepoint" represents

00:04:43.310 --> 00:04:46.480
is my idea of building the
Frankenstein of an agency.

00:04:46.480 --> 00:04:50.110
And we can talk about that
Frankenstein in a good way.

00:04:50.110 --> 00:04:52.800
You know, the perfection
kind of thing.

00:04:52.800 --> 00:04:55.900
But this one was here because
of my publisher, Wiley,

00:04:55.900 --> 00:04:57.690
of the last four books.

00:04:57.690 --> 00:05:01.540
Random House was the first
one, but my publisher

00:05:01.540 --> 00:05:04.660
said what's your next
marketing book, Larry?

00:05:04.660 --> 00:05:07.310
And I said, well, let me see
what's out there right now.

00:05:07.310 --> 00:05:10.560
So I went on Amazon and
I googled things too.

00:05:10.560 --> 00:05:13.640
And I realized that what
is being written even today

00:05:13.640 --> 00:05:15.490
is there's the
experts on search.

00:05:15.490 --> 00:05:18.260
There's the experts on
marketing automation software.

00:05:18.260 --> 00:05:23.180
There's the experts on content
creation and content strategy.

00:05:23.180 --> 00:05:25.350
You name it, a slice.

00:05:25.350 --> 00:05:28.140
But nobody I thought had written
a book like David Ogilvy's

00:05:28.140 --> 00:05:32.250
"Ogilvy on Advertising" where
he sat back in 1965 and went,

00:05:32.250 --> 00:05:37.900
OK, let's look at the entire
New Yorker map of marketing

00:05:37.900 --> 00:05:39.590
and advertising and all that.

00:05:39.590 --> 00:05:42.030
And it was a
brilliant landscape.

00:05:42.030 --> 00:05:44.900
And so what this
book attempts to be

00:05:44.900 --> 00:05:47.710
is let's look at the
entire digital landscape

00:05:47.710 --> 00:05:51.350
of storm software to
search to visual to content

00:05:51.350 --> 00:05:54.930
to a lot of software.

00:05:54.930 --> 00:05:56.790
And then write about
that so that then you

00:05:56.790 --> 00:06:00.470
can dig down instead
of drilling down first,

00:06:00.470 --> 00:06:01.380
get sort of a thing.

00:06:01.380 --> 00:06:02.980
So that's why I write.

00:06:02.980 --> 00:06:04.800
And also, the last
reason I write

00:06:04.800 --> 00:06:06.900
is it's really good
at getting business.

00:06:06.900 --> 00:06:09.390
Because when my competitors
are giving business cards,

00:06:09.390 --> 00:06:10.490
I'm handing out books.

00:06:13.150 --> 00:06:16.960
MALE SPEAKER: So I'll ask one
or two quick follow-ups on that.

00:06:16.960 --> 00:06:18.825
So in some regards,
you didn't even

00:06:18.825 --> 00:06:21.450
anticipate who you were writing
for, like the college students,

00:06:21.450 --> 00:06:22.789
for instance.

00:06:22.789 --> 00:06:25.080
LARRY WEBER: I just got
interested in different topics.

00:06:25.080 --> 00:06:27.740
MALE SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:06:27.740 --> 00:06:30.040
As it relates to it's
a good way to build

00:06:30.040 --> 00:06:35.860
business or different types
of access and exposure,

00:06:35.860 --> 00:06:38.140
specifically as it relates
to the college students,

00:06:38.140 --> 00:06:41.810
how do you see colleges treating
this type of career path

00:06:41.810 --> 00:06:44.980
differently, or do you?

00:06:44.980 --> 00:06:46.690
Places where maybe
they've invited

00:06:46.690 --> 00:06:48.610
you to talk after buying
lots of your books?

00:06:48.610 --> 00:06:51.640
LARRY WEBER: Yeah, a lot of the
marketing, like San Jose State,

00:06:51.640 --> 00:06:54.460
BU, and I think they're
finally getting it.

00:06:54.460 --> 00:06:57.130
They're teaching a little
more around search,

00:06:57.130 --> 00:06:58.450
around content strategies.

00:06:58.450 --> 00:07:02.990
But I think the professors
are still caught up

00:07:02.990 --> 00:07:06.220
in the operational world that
has the head of advertising

00:07:06.220 --> 00:07:09.240
or the head of direct
marketing or the head of PR,

00:07:09.240 --> 00:07:13.240
and they haven't completely
adopted the earned,

00:07:13.240 --> 00:07:18.810
paid and owned media concept
of putting things together.

00:07:18.810 --> 00:07:19.940
I think they're trying.

00:07:19.940 --> 00:07:23.210
I think Columbia is really
trying hard, especially

00:07:23.210 --> 00:07:24.420
in the journalism school.

00:07:24.420 --> 00:07:27.120
To change the way we
view the way content

00:07:27.120 --> 00:07:28.990
is produced and presented.

00:07:28.990 --> 00:07:31.480
But one place that
they're missing

00:07:31.480 --> 00:07:35.860
is this integration of
software, and I have not

00:07:35.860 --> 00:07:37.950
seen that around
when I've talked.

00:07:37.950 --> 00:07:40.100
And the kids get
afraid a little bit,

00:07:40.100 --> 00:07:42.540
and I can't believe this
because most of these kids

00:07:42.540 --> 00:07:46.080
are English majors that are
interested in the marketing.

00:07:46.080 --> 00:07:48.660
Or history majors.

00:07:48.660 --> 00:07:50.880
And I said, you've got to
understand basic coding.

00:07:50.880 --> 00:07:52.151
You just have to.

00:07:52.151 --> 00:07:53.984
You're just going to
have to force yourself.

00:07:53.984 --> 00:07:56.432
It's like eating
spinach when you're 10

00:07:56.432 --> 00:07:58.890
because you're going to have
to understand how to integrate

00:07:58.890 --> 00:08:01.500
the best software tools
you have available to reach

00:08:01.500 --> 00:08:04.190
your customers
directly, consistently,

00:08:04.190 --> 00:08:05.830
and in an engaging way.

00:08:05.830 --> 00:08:09.630
And I think we're
sort of at that period

00:08:09.630 --> 00:08:12.480
that it's really hard
to bring that together.

00:08:12.480 --> 00:08:14.800
But it's going to happen.

00:08:14.800 --> 00:08:18.110
And the other thing I learned
about that, not from schools,

00:08:18.110 --> 00:08:21.730
but was going to spend time--
I was on the board of a company

00:08:21.730 --> 00:08:23.270
we sold to Marketo.

00:08:23.270 --> 00:08:27.050
And so I went and spent
time with that CEO and CMO,

00:08:27.050 --> 00:08:28.970
and then I spent time
with the Eloqua guys,

00:08:28.970 --> 00:08:34.559
and then my friends at
HubSpot, Brian and Dharmesh.

00:08:34.559 --> 00:08:37.730
They hate when I say
this, but we really

00:08:37.730 --> 00:08:39.220
studied those products.

00:08:39.220 --> 00:08:42.650
They're really very simple
and they're not very complex.

00:08:42.650 --> 00:08:44.880
I don't mean they
need to be complex,

00:08:44.880 --> 00:08:47.430
but I think they make mistakes.

00:08:47.430 --> 00:08:50.080
They aren't integrated
properly necessarily

00:08:50.080 --> 00:08:54.510
with Salesforce or other
advanced CRM systems,

00:08:54.510 --> 00:08:55.430
these kinds of things.

00:08:55.430 --> 00:08:59.060
So we're in this
world right now where

00:08:59.060 --> 00:09:03.050
I really think it's like year
one of the new marketing, which

00:09:03.050 --> 00:09:06.750
is going to, again, be
around data software,

00:09:06.750 --> 00:09:10.660
but still creativity and
content and visualization.

00:09:10.660 --> 00:09:13.740
And some schools are
starting to get that,

00:09:13.740 --> 00:09:18.093
but again, it's a different
type of career path.

00:09:18.093 --> 00:09:19.980
And I think what
the kids are looking

00:09:19.980 --> 00:09:23.160
for are companies like
Google to help teach them

00:09:23.160 --> 00:09:24.170
some of those things.

00:09:24.170 --> 00:09:27.610
That they might get the
basics at these universities

00:09:27.610 --> 00:09:33.150
around the basics of purchase
theory and pricing and things

00:09:33.150 --> 00:09:35.850
that marketing and
sales should understand.

00:09:35.850 --> 00:09:40.120
But that I want to go to
Amazon or Google or Facebook

00:09:40.120 --> 00:09:43.350
because they can teach me more
about the future of things,

00:09:43.350 --> 00:09:46.810
which, by the way, is not always
innovative, as I was telling

00:09:46.810 --> 00:09:48.390
Sheryl Sandberg.

00:09:48.390 --> 00:09:51.979
She thought native advertising
two years ago was just so cool.

00:09:51.979 --> 00:09:54.520
I said, you know, Sheryl, we've
been doing that for 30 years.

00:09:54.520 --> 00:09:59.030
We called it advertorials,
and we labeled it an ad.

00:09:59.030 --> 00:10:05.590
So there's a lot of inventing
of things that's going on,

00:10:05.590 --> 00:10:10.390
but what is changing is the
objectives of marketing.

00:10:10.390 --> 00:10:12.770
I think it should be more
about engagement time

00:10:12.770 --> 00:10:19.250
and less about the purchase
and more about the engagement.

00:10:19.250 --> 00:10:22.660
You know, the shareability,
those kinds of things.

00:10:22.660 --> 00:10:24.500
So, anyway.

00:10:24.500 --> 00:10:26.735
MALE SPEAKER: So just as
a quick poll question--

00:10:26.735 --> 00:10:28.010
LARRY WEBER: I could go on.

00:10:28.010 --> 00:10:29.190
MALE SPEAKER: What's that?

00:10:29.190 --> 00:10:30.650
LARRY WEBER: I just said
I could go on and on.

00:10:30.650 --> 00:10:31.030
MALE SPEAKER: I know.

00:10:31.030 --> 00:10:32.180
That's why you're here.

00:10:32.180 --> 00:10:33.014
LARRY WEBER: Oh, OK.

00:10:33.014 --> 00:10:34.596
MALE SPEAKER: That's
why I didn't have

00:10:34.596 --> 00:10:36.040
to write too many questions.

00:10:36.040 --> 00:10:38.890
How many had a major that was
something like a liberal arts

00:10:38.890 --> 00:10:42.460
major in this room?

00:10:42.460 --> 00:10:45.830
And how many had
a business major?

00:10:45.830 --> 00:10:47.080
LARRY WEBER: Computer science?

00:10:47.080 --> 00:10:49.121
MALE SPEAKER: And how many
had a computer science

00:10:49.121 --> 00:10:50.310
oriented major?

00:10:50.310 --> 00:10:52.224
So weighted towards the--

00:10:52.224 --> 00:10:53.890
LARRY WEBER: Well,
it's good that you're

00:10:53.890 --> 00:10:56.670
all in the same room.

00:10:56.670 --> 00:11:03.400
When I started 35 years
ago, IT was just beginning.

00:11:03.400 --> 00:11:07.480
I mean, we look so different in
marketing versus the IT guys.

00:11:07.480 --> 00:11:09.920
And then I remember
over the years

00:11:09.920 --> 00:11:12.890
in Boston, all of a sudden there
were all these-- by the way,

00:11:12.890 --> 00:11:15.980
there were only two C titles
when I started in business.

00:11:15.980 --> 00:11:18.270
There was the CEO and the CFO.

00:11:18.270 --> 00:11:20.710
And then all of a
sudden, this Fortune 500

00:11:20.710 --> 00:11:23.470
company I was working
with had a COO,

00:11:23.470 --> 00:11:27.050
and I was intrigued to see what
their responsibilities were.

00:11:27.050 --> 00:11:29.750
I read the responsibilities, and
they seem like the same stuff

00:11:29.750 --> 00:11:32.690
the CEO and the CFO
was supposed to do.

00:11:32.690 --> 00:11:37.322
And anyway, I moved
here in early 1982,

00:11:37.322 --> 00:11:39.280
and that's when I got
into technology marketing

00:11:39.280 --> 00:11:41.740
because I mistakenly went
to a party-- or actually,

00:11:41.740 --> 00:11:43.460
fortunately went
to a party and met

00:11:43.460 --> 00:11:46.450
a barefoot guy named Mitch Kapor
who was starting a software

00:11:46.450 --> 00:11:47.390
company called Lotus.

00:11:47.390 --> 00:11:50.830
And we hit it off and introduced
most of their products.

00:11:50.830 --> 00:11:55.260
But anyway, there were all these
titles back then called MIS.

00:11:55.260 --> 00:11:58.640
I mean, some of the older people
must remember MIS-- managers

00:11:58.640 --> 00:12:00.750
of information services.

00:12:00.750 --> 00:12:02.520
And companies hired
so many of those

00:12:02.520 --> 00:12:05.880
that they had another
C title-- CTOs.

00:12:05.880 --> 00:12:08.380
And then all those people
started buying all the software

00:12:08.380 --> 00:12:10.800
and the CTOs didn't
understand the software,

00:12:10.800 --> 00:12:12.910
so they have a CIO.

00:12:12.910 --> 00:12:15.230
And then we went through
this period in the '90s

00:12:15.230 --> 00:12:18.120
where everybody was making
so much money that we decided

00:12:18.120 --> 00:12:20.790
to have titles like
chief talent officer

00:12:20.790 --> 00:12:26.390
and chief knowledge officer
and chief strategic officer.

00:12:26.390 --> 00:12:32.250
And then in the 2000s, which
I think is fascinating,

00:12:32.250 --> 00:12:35.790
is the fastest growing title in
corporate America, especially

00:12:35.790 --> 00:12:38.650
a CMO.

00:12:38.650 --> 00:12:43.000
And I think it's easy to
deduce then that every time we

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:44.970
have a really fucked up
