And this should be
one agency offering.

00:26:07.130 --> 00:26:08.330
It shouldn't just be.

00:26:08.330 --> 00:26:12.382
And so that's when we started
to really integrate everything.

00:26:12.382 --> 00:26:14.090
But we have to lead
with a point of view,

00:26:14.090 --> 00:26:16.000
and that's what I
call earned media,

00:26:16.000 --> 00:26:17.930
which is a fancy name for PR.

00:26:17.930 --> 00:26:20.090
So how do you get
covered in the blogs?

00:26:20.090 --> 00:26:22.020
How do you get
covered on TechCrunch?

00:26:22.020 --> 00:26:24.380
How do you get covered
in wallstreetjournal.com,

00:26:24.380 --> 00:26:27.430
forbes.com, all
that kind of stuff.

00:26:27.430 --> 00:26:30.805
But we quickly move then
to a creative department,

00:26:30.805 --> 00:26:32.780
a technology department.

00:26:32.780 --> 00:26:35.550
We've developed two software
products around influence

00:26:35.550 --> 00:26:39.550
so that we could identify the
100 most influential people

00:26:39.550 --> 00:26:41.850
to a specific
company or a product

00:26:41.850 --> 00:26:44.840
and what are their
social properties?

00:26:44.840 --> 00:26:46.670
So we know what
one reporter really

00:26:46.670 --> 00:26:49.080
likes to tweet, another
one doesn't, who

00:26:49.080 --> 00:26:54.170
their friends are on Facebook,
et cetera, kind of things.

00:26:54.170 --> 00:26:58.280
So we're really working deeply
from an influence perspective,

00:26:58.280 --> 00:27:00.810
and then I argue that
the future of an agency

00:27:00.810 --> 00:27:03.840
is going to be about a new
solar system model where

00:27:03.840 --> 00:27:06.780
the sun-- if you take
this metaphor-- the sun is

00:27:06.780 --> 00:27:09.740
the customer and all the
planets going around it

00:27:09.740 --> 00:27:13.160
are things like marketing
automation, software, content,

00:27:13.160 --> 00:27:16.420
visualization, data
analytics, all that.

00:27:16.420 --> 00:27:20.680
And some of those are all going
to collide and become together

00:27:20.680 --> 00:27:21.880
kinds of things.

00:27:21.880 --> 00:27:26.750
But it's going to be an
interesting time right now.

00:27:26.750 --> 00:27:30.710
There's a reason that there
wasn't a marketing ERP system

00:27:30.710 --> 00:27:32.940
and every other
category had one.

00:27:32.940 --> 00:27:37.850
HR was PeopleSoft, finance
was SAP, database was Oracle.

00:27:37.850 --> 00:27:41.250
You can go down the line.

00:27:41.250 --> 00:27:45.750
And I think the reason
is, one, Madison Avenue

00:27:45.750 --> 00:27:48.940
Mafia, and London and
Paris now, who are trying

00:27:48.940 --> 00:27:51.674
to keep television alive.

00:27:51.674 --> 00:27:54.340
And how they're going to do that
is combining more with you guys

00:27:54.340 --> 00:27:59.700
and doing as much as they
can to prop up the media

00:27:59.700 --> 00:28:01.450
spends that they have.

00:28:01.450 --> 00:28:04.960
But my view is
that there's going

00:28:04.960 --> 00:28:07.870
to be an alignment
of consulting,

00:28:07.870 --> 00:28:10.990
of creative technology
of software.

00:28:10.990 --> 00:28:13.200
Deloitte, for example,
bunch of accountants

00:28:13.200 --> 00:28:15.200
just bought a San
Francisco digital agency.

00:28:15.200 --> 00:28:20.080
Interesting to me that they
now could do everything

00:28:20.080 --> 00:28:23.780
from conceptual consulting,
much like a Bain

00:28:23.780 --> 00:28:28.390
or a BCG, all the way through
execution of a campaign,

00:28:28.390 --> 00:28:30.160
digitally.

00:28:30.160 --> 00:28:34.140
And then we see competitors
from any given day,

00:28:34.140 --> 00:28:40.750
Sapient and Digitas to Ogilvy
is a big competitor of ours now,

00:28:40.750 --> 00:28:43.280
to the big PR firms, who
are actually really lagging

00:28:43.280 --> 00:28:47.380
still because PR is
still a category that

00:28:47.380 --> 00:28:50.350
waits for stuff to
happen and then reacts

00:28:50.350 --> 00:28:53.500
versus being very aggressive
about making things happen,

00:28:53.500 --> 00:28:56.280
which is more the paid
side of the world.

00:28:56.280 --> 00:29:01.150
And so, it's been a
fascinating time right now.

00:29:01.150 --> 00:29:02.650
But I think that
the next five years

00:29:02.650 --> 00:29:05.040
are going to be interesting
in this convergence,

00:29:05.040 --> 00:29:08.080
and I think
companies like Google

00:29:08.080 --> 00:29:09.860
are right at the heart of this.

00:29:09.860 --> 00:29:12.730
As one of the sumo wrestlers
for the heart and soul

00:29:12.730 --> 00:29:15.560
of the future of the web.

00:29:15.560 --> 00:29:18.780
And I don't know if you seen
the tech or the Venture Beat

00:29:18.780 --> 00:29:22.220
article last week on
the era of messaging?

00:29:22.220 --> 00:29:23.600
Has anybody seen that?

00:29:23.600 --> 00:29:27.350
I recommend looking
at that article

00:29:27.350 --> 00:29:28.960
as it will impact your business.

00:29:28.960 --> 00:29:31.070
And I thought they
want a little too far.

00:29:31.070 --> 00:29:33.705
That messaging is going
to be so explosive

00:29:33.705 --> 00:29:37.650
and that's going to be a new
advertising model and marketing

00:29:37.650 --> 00:29:41.680
model, but it's another
play in the thing.

00:29:41.680 --> 00:29:44.980
I'm on the board of the largest
social network in Africa.

00:29:44.980 --> 00:29:51.930
It's called MIXT-- M-I-X-T-- and
it's a feature phone kind of.

00:29:51.930 --> 00:29:55.720
So more like a WhatsApp
for Africa kind of thing.

00:29:55.720 --> 00:29:58.760
And it's interesting to see the
different uses of messaging.

00:30:01.112 --> 00:30:03.070
I'm sure you guys are
studying this completely.

00:30:03.070 --> 00:30:06.770
But in this last book, I talk a
lot about if I was a young kid

00:30:06.770 --> 00:30:08.390
and I was interested
in marketing,

00:30:08.390 --> 00:30:11.730
I'd get into loyalty,
digital loyalty or couponing.

00:30:11.730 --> 00:30:14.830
I think that is still
in the dark ages,

00:30:14.830 --> 00:30:17.300
and how that's going
to happen contextually.

00:30:17.300 --> 00:30:18.880
I'll give you an example.

00:30:18.880 --> 00:30:21.825
I was on a panel with Howard
Schultz two years ago,

00:30:21.825 --> 00:30:26.020
a year and a half
ago in Washington.

00:30:26.020 --> 00:30:28.790
And after, we were all talking
afterwards, and he said,

00:30:28.790 --> 00:30:31.470
would you be a guinea
pig for a marketing thing

00:30:31.470 --> 00:30:32.890
we're trying to
do with Starbucks?

00:30:32.890 --> 00:30:34.670
And I said, OK, sure.

00:30:34.670 --> 00:30:38.700
And I didn't hear anything from
him or anybody from Starbucks.

00:30:38.700 --> 00:30:41.190
But about a month
later, I get an email

00:30:41.190 --> 00:30:43.740
to introduce the person in
the marketing department

00:30:43.740 --> 00:30:48.950
at Starbucks and said thanks
for agreeing to do this test

00:30:48.950 --> 00:30:50.400
program with us.

00:30:50.400 --> 00:30:53.700
And would you fill out
this sort of survey.

00:30:53.700 --> 00:30:58.650
It was like SurveyMonkey,
only customized to Starbucks.

00:30:58.650 --> 00:31:01.110
And it asked me questions
like when you go to Starbucks,

00:31:01.110 --> 00:31:02.780
what time usually is it?

00:31:02.780 --> 00:31:04.560
What's your favorite
thing you order?

00:31:04.560 --> 00:31:07.300
If you order food,
what food do you order?

00:31:07.300 --> 00:31:09.400
Do you buy for your
family or other people,

00:31:09.400 --> 00:31:13.170
or is it pretty much, so
does somebody buy for you?

00:31:13.170 --> 00:31:15.890
And so they were asking
some pretty good questions

00:31:15.890 --> 00:31:18.679
even though it was only about
eight to nine questions.

00:31:18.679 --> 00:31:20.720
And then would you give
us your cellphone number,

00:31:20.720 --> 00:31:22.570
and I said sure.

00:31:22.570 --> 00:31:25.860
By the way, I'm from the Scott
McNealy school of privacy.

00:31:25.860 --> 00:31:28.180
I don't believe
it exists anymore.

00:31:28.180 --> 00:31:30.700
I'm OK with it, except
in the future I think--

00:31:30.700 --> 00:31:31.310
MALE SPEAKER: You're
going to have to tell

00:31:31.310 --> 00:31:32.600
everyone who Scott McNealy is.

00:31:32.600 --> 00:31:34.391
LARRY WEBER: Oh, he
was one of the founders

00:31:34.391 --> 00:31:38.330
of Sun Microsystems that
was bought by Oracle.

00:31:38.330 --> 00:31:43.980
And they had the software, Java
was one of their big software

00:31:43.980 --> 00:31:45.380
platforms.

00:31:45.380 --> 00:31:47.400
Anybody uses Java anymore?

00:31:47.400 --> 00:31:51.750
But anyway, he also
said privacy is dead.

00:31:51.750 --> 00:31:52.619
Get over it.

00:31:52.619 --> 00:31:54.910
But I do think it's going to
be an important discussion

00:31:54.910 --> 00:31:55.860
around health data.

00:31:55.860 --> 00:31:57.407
But I don't care
if somebody knows I

00:31:57.407 --> 00:31:58.990
like pink shirts
from Brooks Brothers.

00:31:58.990 --> 00:31:59.970
I really don't.

00:31:59.970 --> 00:32:02.000
In fact, it should
work in my advantage

00:32:02.000 --> 00:32:04.770
that somebody knows
that kind of thing.

00:32:08.390 --> 00:32:12.125
To finish the Starbucks story,
so I forgot about it again

00:32:12.125 --> 00:32:13.950
because they didn't do anything.

00:32:13.950 --> 00:32:16.090
I didn't get any
offers or anything.

00:32:16.090 --> 00:32:19.470
So I'm with my middle
daughter in London.

00:32:19.470 --> 00:32:21.520
She had some time
off-- or no, I know.

00:32:21.520 --> 00:32:24.400
She was doing one of those
junior year things in Edinburgh

00:32:24.400 --> 00:32:27.080
and I had her come down
to London to see a show.

00:32:27.080 --> 00:32:34.207
And so we were waking up
at the hotel and I said,

00:32:34.207 --> 00:32:36.040
well, let's go get some
breakfast somewhere.

00:32:36.040 --> 00:32:40.060
And right when I
said that-- that was,

00:32:40.060 --> 00:32:43.455
I'm sure, coincidental-- I
get a text from Starbucks.

00:32:43.455 --> 00:32:44.080
And it's says--

00:32:44.080 --> 00:32:44.486
MALE SPEAKER: All of
that was coincidental?

00:32:44.486 --> 00:32:46.550
LARRY WEBER: Yeah,
I say, Hi, Larry.

00:32:46.550 --> 00:32:47.840
It says, hi, Larry.

00:32:47.840 --> 00:32:49.370
Why don't you come
across the street

00:32:49.370 --> 00:32:53.610
to 325 Kensington High Street
for your free iced espresso,

00:32:53.610 --> 00:32:57.780
and we'll give you 25 pounds
off your breakfast sandwich.

00:32:57.780 --> 00:33:00.620
And I went, Julia,
let's go over there.

00:33:00.620 --> 00:33:02.050
I think this is cool.

00:33:02.050 --> 00:33:06.745
Julia being a 21-year-old coed
at one of those fancy schools

00:33:06.745 --> 00:33:10.430
that costs too much said,
Dad, that's sort of creepy.

00:33:10.430 --> 00:33:15.810
They could have sent
a drone on top of you.

00:33:15.810 --> 00:33:19.100
I'm like, well, now let's
go see if this works.

00:33:19.100 --> 00:33:20.840
So we went in and
I said I think I

00:33:20.840 --> 00:33:24.140
have a free iced
espresso and some money

00:33:24.140 --> 00:33:25.740
off a breakfast sandwich.

00:33:25.740 --> 00:33:29.560
And she says, OK, I
haven't seen that before.

00:33:29.560 --> 00:33:33.050
But you know, so I held
it up and it goes through.

00:33:33.050 --> 00:33:35.680
And so I get it and I
thought that was pretty cool.

00:33:35.680 --> 00:33:38.580
And then I started
thinking about all that

00:33:38.580 --> 00:33:41.372
must have had to go into that.

00:33:41.372 --> 00:33:42.830
And I started
thinking about things

00:33:42.830 --> 00:33:47.550
like contextual marketing, and
predictive analytics, which

00:33:47.550 --> 00:33:49.350
are going to be the
two of the biggest

00:33:49.350 --> 00:33:51.460
areas in the next few years.

00:33:51.460 --> 00:33:53.920
And I was thinking, well,
what if they offered me

00:33:53.920 --> 00:33:57.870
like an iced herbal tea
and I hate herbal tea?

00:33:57.870 --> 00:34:00.430
And they would have
set the relationship

00:34:00.430 --> 00:34:04.100
back a little with me, even
though it was a free offer.

00:34:04.100 --> 00:34:06.030
So that's what I mean
about the complexity

00:34:06.030 --> 00:34:08.540
in the future of this
sort of digital loyalty

00:34:08.540 --> 00:34:10.750
and points and programming.

00:34:10.750 --> 00:34:12.429
And then I was
trying to use points

00:34:12.429 --> 00:34:15.525
to go down to see a college with
my youngest son the other day.

00:34:15.525 --> 00:34:16.900
And it was such
a pain in the ass

00:34:16.900 --> 00:34:20.020
to try to use my
delta points still.

00:34:20.020 --> 00:34:22.860
And I'm like, who's going
to come up with-- just,

00:34:22.860 --> 00:34:23.870
it is so easy.

00:34:23.870 --> 00:34:27.820
Mr. Weber, you have
900,000 points,

00:34:27.820 --> 00:34:32.130
and I still had to pay
full price for my ticket.

00:34:32.130 --> 00:34:37.670
And I was like, my god,
this is just insane.

00:34:37.670 --> 00:34:40.409
I should be able to just
hold up that smartphone.

00:34:40.409 --> 00:34:44.150
You guys organize it-- you,
Delta, or I'm going to JetBlue.

00:34:44.150 --> 00:34:45.060
You organize it.

00:34:45.060 --> 00:34:47.340
I don't want to
have numbers, cards.

00:34:47.340 --> 00:34:48.520
I don't want any of that.

00:34:51.929 --> 00:34:54.141
You also hit a loyalty
nerve with me there.

00:34:54.141 --> 00:34:56.765
MALE SPEAKER: I had exactly the
same conversation with somebody

00:34:56.765 --> 00:34:58.530
maybe in this room,
but certainly someone

00:34:58.530 --> 00:35:02.150
here at Google in the last
week about United and exactly

00:35:02.150 --> 00:35:04.230
the same conversation.

00:35:04.230 --> 00:35:07.192
It was painful That was
a painful experience.

00:35:07.192 --> 00:35:08.900
Does anyone have any
questions for Larry?

00:35:08.900 --> 00:35:11.281
OK, good, because I have
more, but I should shut up.

00:35:11.281 --> 00:35:12.280
LARRY WEBER: Is this OK?

00:35:12.280 --> 00:35:15.120
Is this making
sense for you guys?

00:35:15.120 --> 00:35:15.662
OK.

00:35:15.662 --> 00:35:17.620
I can answer things about
the future of search,

00:35:17.620 --> 00:35:18.646
too, if you want.

00:35:18.646 --> 00:35:19.520
AUDIENCE: Hey, Larry.

00:35:19.520 --> 00:35:20.650
Thanks for being here.

00:35:20.650 --> 00:35:22.430
Quick question.

00:35:22.430 --> 00:35:25.067
It's more of a hypothetical
desert island scenario.

00:35:25.067 --> 00:35:27.400
If you were taken out of your
current position and said,

00:35:27.400 --> 00:35:31.760
OK, you have to start a
widget company from scratch,

00:35:31.760 --> 00:35:34.130
limited budget,
what's your hierarchy

00:35:34.130 --> 00:35:35.840
of needs for techniques?

00:35:35.840 --> 00:35:37.900
Because when we're
talking to clients

00:35:37.900 --> 00:35:40.130
and they think this
omnichannel, they're

00:35:40.130 --> 00:35:44.290
often having a conversation
with us as, OK, search, display.

00:35:44.290 --> 00:35:46.130
They start talking
about things and what

00:35:46.130 --> 00:35:48.780
they think the opportunity
cost of this dollar spent

00:35:48.780 --> 00:35:49.682
here or that.

00:35:49.682 --> 00:35:51.140
And then they start
thinking, well,

00:35:51.140 --> 00:35:52.990
does PR give us SEO benefit?

00:35:52.990 --> 00:35:54.720
Does this happen?

00:35:54.720 --> 00:35:55.820
We have limited people.

00:35:55.820 --> 00:35:56.890
We have limited money.

00:35:56.890 --> 00:35:59.090
So if I put you in
a scenario where

00:35:59.090 --> 00:36:02.460
you are supposed to build
a brand from scratch

00:36:02.460 --> 00:36:04.550
and you don't have any of
your current resources,

00:36:04.550 --> 00:36:06.550
how do you go about
building that plan?

00:36:06.550 --> 00:36:08.260
LARRY WEBER: Yeah,
that's easy for me.

00:36:08.260 --> 00:36:10.360
Good question.

00:36:10.360 --> 00:36:13.040
I am not a big
believer in quant,

00:36:13.040 --> 00:36:17.750
So that makes me pitted against
a lot of people right away.

00:36:17.750 --> 00:36:19.150
Because they want quant.

00:36:19.150 --> 00:36:23.130
They want massive
reach to customers

00:36:23.130 --> 00:36:25.360
and they want it
right away and they

00:36:25.360 --> 00:36:28.840
want startups to scale
right away, and this.

00:36:28.840 --> 00:36:31.710
What I would argue to build
a great lasting brand today,

00:36:31.710 --> 00:36:34.210
and I talk with Reid Hoffman
about this all the time.

00:36:34.210 --> 00:36:36.829
He thinks LinkedIn will
last for a hundred years,

00:36:36.829 --> 00:36:38.370
and that's what
they're trying to do.

00:36:38.370 --> 00:36:41.450
And I think it'll be replaced
just like Monster was.

00:36:41.450 --> 00:36:45.890
But anyway, what I
would do is I would

00:36:45.890 --> 00:36:47.970
have strategies,
marketing strategies,

00:36:47.970 --> 00:36:49.730
around engaging customers.

00:36:49.730 --> 00:36:53.300
And I would measure the
length of engagement,

00:36:53.300 --> 00:36:55.930
the content that's working,
the content that's not working,

00:36:55.930 --> 00:36:58.300
and I would enlist listen
as the sales people.

00:36:58.300 --> 00:37:02.240
How do you create a brand
around some kind of passion?

00:37:02.240 --> 00:37:06.020
And I think even old companies
can reinvent that way.

00:37:06.020 --> 00:37:08.520
One of the coolest
assignments we have right now,

00:37:08.520 --> 00:37:10.550
which took nine
months of fighting

00:37:10.550 --> 00:37:13.830
against the heads of marketing.

00:37:13.830 --> 00:37:16.090
There's a company
called John Deere,

00:37:16.090 --> 00:37:19.210
and I was having a
drink with its CEO

00:37:19.210 --> 00:37:21.130
who said to me after two drinks.

00:37:21.130 --> 00:37:23.560
He said, Larry, I don't know
what my legacy's going to be.

00:37:23.560 --> 00:37:27.670
I don't want it to be that I
just sold more green tractors.

00:37:27.670 --> 00:37:29.300
And so we started
talking about this,

00:37:29.300 --> 00:37:31.050
and there's a reason
I'm bringing this up.

00:37:31.050 --> 00:37:33.370
Because it can be
done for startups too.

00:37:33.370 --> 00:37:35.710
And I said, well, let's see.

00:37:35.710 --> 00:37:37.910
Let's look at the facts
about where you live.

00:37:37.910 --> 00:37:40.410
You're a $50 billion
company and you're

00:37:40.410 --> 00:37:44.130
collecting more farm data than
anybody on the planet, right?

00:37:44.130 --> 00:37:47.570
And his assistant or
one of his sidekicks

00:37:47.570 --> 00:37:51.480
was quoting these numbers so I
could get a picture in my head.

00:37:51.480 --> 00:37:54.760
That when I was a kid, there
were 22,000 farms in America.

00:37:54.760 --> 00:37:58.440
Today, there's 8,000 farms, but
they're are three times as big

00:37:58.440 --> 00:38:00.090
and they're also
really complicated

00:38:00.090 --> 00:38:04.840
on whether soil
content, fertilizer.

00:38:04.840 --> 00:38:09.810
I mean, you name the data that
is needed to manage a farm.

00:38:09.810 --> 00:38:12.190
And then they started talking
about their peer group,

00:38:12.190 --> 00:38:16.380
and that their peer group
is Caterpillar and Kubota.

00:38:16.380 --> 00:38:18.690
And then somebody
mentioned too that there's

00:38:18.690 --> 00:38:21.280
going to be two billion more
people that have to be fed

00:38:21.280 --> 00:38:22.960
and we can't ruin the planet.

00:38:22.960 --> 00:38:26.200
How do we have a better yield
and how do we sort of do

00:38:26.200 --> 00:38:28.970
good and that kind of stuff.

00:38:28.970 --> 00:38:31.330
And so we went back
with a program that

00:38:31.330 --> 00:38:34.230
said forget your peers are
Caterpillar and Kubota.

00:38:34.230 --> 00:38:35.710
Just forget it.

00:38:35.710 --> 00:38:40.720
Your peers are Google,
Amazon, and Apple, John Deere.

00:38:40.720 --> 00:38:44.680
And of course, they looked
at me like I had three heads

00:38:44.680 --> 00:38:46.770
because they're like, no.

00:38:46.770 --> 00:38:47.800
We don't understand.

00:38:47.800 --> 00:38:50.030
We don't compete with Amazon.

00:38:50.030 --> 00:38:51.790
I said, it's not
about competition.

00:38:51.790 --> 00:38:55.609
It's how you approach the way
and the work that you're doing,

00:38:55.609 --> 00:38:57.650
and how you're going to
be innovative about this.

00:38:57.650 --> 00:39:00.860
They had so much software
that they had developed

00:39:00.860 --> 00:39:03.770
to help manage farms and data.

00:39:03.770 --> 00:39:08.320
And so we're now working on this
huge program about how they're

00:39:08.320 --> 00:39:09.800
not really about the tractors.

00:39:09.800 --> 00:39:10.960
Yes they are.

00:39:10.960 --> 00:39:13.480
But they're about feeding
the next $2 billion people

00:39:13.480 --> 00:39:16.630
and they're about helping
manage farms smarter and better

00:39:16.630 --> 00:39:17.840
and more effectively.

00:39:17.840 --> 00:39:20.510
And this led me to
a marketing theory,

00:39:20.510 --> 00:39:23.535
even for smaller
companies, that you know

00:39:23.535 --> 00:39:24.750
what is going to happen now?

00:39:24.750 --> 00:39:26.890
And this is a really
scary prediction.

00:39:26.890 --> 00:39:28.890
I actually think big
software companies

00:39:28.890 --> 00:39:30.880
are going to fail long term.

00:39:30.880 --> 00:39:34.280
I think you're going to
see Oracle and SAP-- I

00:39:34.280 --> 00:39:36.840
think these companies are
going to have a lot of trouble.

00:39:36.840 --> 00:39:38.320
And I think what's
going to happen

00:39:38.320 --> 00:39:42.450
is you're going to see GM,
John Deere, they're hiring

00:39:42.450 --> 00:39:43.920
more and more developers.

00:39:43.920 --> 00:39:46.460
They're customizing
more and more software.

00:39:46.460 --> 00:39:48.470
They're managing more
data and analytics,

00:39:48.470 --> 00:39:53.030
and they're engaging customers
with important decision making

00:39:53.030 --> 00:39:53.910
tools.

00:39:53.910 --> 00:39:56.460
And I think Google has got
to sit in the middle of that,

00:39:56.460 --> 00:39:58.950
but I also think that's where
your marketing strategy has

00:39:58.950 --> 00:39:59.780
to go.

00:39:59.780 --> 00:40:02.560
So there's a company
spinning out.

00:40:02.560 --> 00:40:04.770
You guys must know this
company spinning out

00:40:04.770 --> 00:40:06.660
of MIT called Ditto.

00:40:06.660 --> 00:40:08.690
And they have a
really cool technology

00:40:08.690 --> 00:40:13.410
around analyzing
videos and photographs.

00:40:13.410 --> 00:40:15.990
They know where you bought
that shirt by analyzing it

00:40:15.990 --> 00:40:18.040
on Facebook or Instagram.

00:40:18.040 --> 00:40:23.390
Now don't ask me how they
can do that one, all right?

00:40:23.390 --> 00:40:24.710
But same thing.

00:40:24.710 --> 00:40:27.740
How do you both start
to get that message out

00:40:27.740 --> 00:40:29.390
to marketers and
to the customers

00:40:29.390 --> 00:40:31.850
that they want in a more
educated way, not in

00:40:31.850 --> 00:40:33.710
an in your face way.

00:40:33.710 --> 00:40:37.510
And how do you create engagement
and content strategies

00:40:37.510 --> 00:40:39.200
and things like that?

00:40:39.200 --> 00:40:41.410
And then on the earned
media site when you said PR,

00:40:41.410 --> 00:40:43.870
I still think that
carries a lot of weight.

00:40:43.870 --> 00:40:46.490
Look at TripAdvisor alone.

00:40:46.490 --> 00:40:49.710
I was talking to the CEO.

00:40:49.710 --> 00:40:52.710
It looks like you're going to
be sued by the country of Mexico

00:40:52.710 --> 00:40:57.010
because there's so many
bad reviews of the beaches

00:40:57.010 --> 00:41:01.582
and the resorts in Mexico
that the government feels

00:41:01.582 --> 00:41:04.040
that their businesses there
have lost like $4 billion or $5

00:41:04.040 --> 00:41:06.840
billion and they're
blaming TripAdvisor.

00:41:06.840 --> 00:41:08.380
Of course, I would
just say, well,

00:41:08.380 --> 00:41:11.300
make the beach nicer, right?

00:41:11.300 --> 00:41:15.480
Make me a stronger drink
or something like that.

00:41:15.480 --> 00:41:19.080
But a part of what
is also wasted--

00:41:19.080 --> 00:41:21.610
and I wish Google would
spend time on this too,

00:41:21.610 --> 00:41:24.170
or somebody would-- is
we don't have the metrics

00:41:24.170 --> 00:41:25.750
in this new generation
of marketing

00:41:25.750 --> 00:41:28.430
that the '60s, '70s,
'80s, or the "Mad Men"

00:41:28.430 --> 00:41:31.310
had with CPMs and all that.

00:41:31.310 --> 00:41:35.170
They were so good at
bullshitting the client on what

00:41:35.170 --> 00:41:36.880
was really measurable.

00:41:36.880 --> 00:41:38.980
And we don't have that.

00:41:38.980 --> 00:41:41.540
Nobody's grabbing
the baton and saying

00:41:41.540 --> 00:41:44.030
is engagement time import?

00:41:44.030 --> 00:41:45.685
Is a share index important?

00:41:48.640 --> 00:41:50.410
Nobody talks about
organic search anymore.

00:41:50.410 --> 00:41:52.070
We were talking
about it at lunch.

00:41:52.070 --> 00:41:53.200
How important that is.

00:41:53.200 --> 00:41:54.620
It's not just the paid search.

00:41:54.620 --> 00:41:56.570
It's, gee, I googled
20 times today,

00:41:56.570 --> 00:41:58.160
and I got the
information I want.

00:41:58.160 --> 00:42:00.780
Or I did make a purchase with
the small company I've never

00:42:00.780 --> 00:42:04.120
worked with before,
and that kind of thing.

00:42:04.120 --> 00:42:07.430
So anyway, I think there's
a whole metric world that

00:42:07.430 --> 00:42:09.590
hasn't been brought together.

00:42:09.590 --> 00:42:12.400
That's a long answer, too.

00:42:12.400 --> 00:42:14.569
But we're paying
bloggers more and more,

00:42:14.569 --> 00:42:16.860
so that's another strategy
that I think is interesting.

00:42:20.200 --> 00:42:21.020
AUDIENCE: Hello.

00:42:21.020 --> 00:42:21.910
LARRY WEBER: Hi.

00:42:21.910 --> 00:42:24.390
AUDIENCE: So you were talking
about the Frankenstein agency

00:42:24.390 --> 00:42:26.470
and how everything is
going to be integrated

00:42:26.470 --> 00:42:27.970
and talking to each other.

00:42:27.970 --> 00:42:32.450
Can you share how you think
mobile is going to affect that?

00:42:32.450 --> 00:42:34.470
What's going to be the
tipping point for mobile?

00:42:34.470 --> 00:42:38.800
And when you think companies are
going to actually start caring?

00:42:38.800 --> 00:42:39.550
LARRY WEBER: Yeah.

00:42:43.950 --> 00:42:46.090
Well, first, I come
from the school

00:42:46.090 --> 00:42:47.800
that there's no such
thing as mobile.

00:42:47.800 --> 00:42:51.640
So I think just
everything is mobile.

00:42:51.640 --> 00:42:57.140
You can take anything
anywhere, I guess.

00:42:57.140 --> 00:43:00.280
I think companies want, again,
to see that metric result.

00:43:00.280 --> 00:43:02.070
That if they're doing
loyalty programs,

00:43:02.070 --> 00:43:04.010
like Starbucks
was testing on me,

00:43:04.010 --> 00:43:07.220
they want to see that that's
really working from a loyalty

00:43:07.220 --> 00:43:07.900
perspective.

00:43:07.900 --> 00:43:10.341
So I think there's a real
measurement thing to mobile

00:43:10.341 --> 00:43:10.840
around.

00:43:10.840 --> 00:43:12.320
I don't think it's
around banners.

00:43:12.320 --> 00:43:16.890
I don't think it's around
that kind of mobile marketing.

00:43:16.890 --> 00:43:20.510
I think it's going to be about
community building, engagement,

00:43:20.510 --> 00:43:23.740
messaging I think is
going to be important.

00:43:23.740 --> 00:43:26.320
Couponing, loyalty, all
those kinds of stuff.

00:43:26.320 --> 00:43:28.280
And some companies
are really getting it.

00:43:28.280 --> 00:43:33.120
I mean, business to business
companies aren't as much yet.

00:43:33.120 --> 00:43:38.280
But Deere is using
mobile apps to show

00:43:38.280 --> 00:43:39.890
how you can get better yield.

00:43:39.890 --> 00:43:42.950
So you have to show
both the information

00:43:42.950 --> 00:43:45.390
and the data side as
well as the sales side

00:43:45.390 --> 00:43:50.994
in some of these kinds
of efforts are stories.

00:43:50.994 --> 00:43:52.410
But I think obviously
everything's

00:43:52.410 --> 00:43:55.360
going to be a smartphone driven.

00:43:55.360 --> 00:43:56.570
I'm not sure about the watch.

00:43:56.570 --> 00:43:59.860
Is that coming out this week?

00:43:59.860 --> 00:44:03.200
I'm just not sure if
that's just a paradigm

00:44:03.200 --> 00:44:05.360
trying to make an
old paradigm better.

00:44:05.360 --> 00:44:07.345
I just don't know.

00:44:10.570 --> 00:44:15.390
I definitely wouldn't
pay $17,000 for a watch,

00:44:15.390 --> 00:44:18.640
but I think the more
senior people that

00:44:18.640 --> 00:44:21.070
come to me are they're
looking for brand engagement.

00:44:21.070 --> 00:44:22.970
How are we going
to engage audiences

00:44:22.970 --> 00:44:24.990
for a long period of time?

00:44:24.990 --> 00:44:27.820
So I'm less in the
transaction business

00:44:27.820 --> 00:44:32.280
and more in the engagement
and brand engagement business.

00:44:32.280 --> 00:44:34.530
Because I think brand is
defined as the conversation

00:44:34.530 --> 00:44:35.710
you have with your customer.

00:44:35.710 --> 00:44:37.960
The weaker the conversation,
the weaker your brand is.

00:44:37.960 --> 00:44:40.820
The stronger the conversation,
the stronger your brand.

00:44:40.820 --> 00:44:43.249
Of course there's a
quant side to everything.

00:44:43.249 --> 00:44:45.040
How are we going to
sell more orange juice?

00:44:47.720 --> 00:44:49.780
And I think all the
analytic companies,

00:44:49.780 --> 00:44:51.390
we may have way
too many of them,

00:44:51.390 --> 00:44:55.660
but I think they're working hard
on all that kind of software

00:44:55.660 --> 00:44:57.470
to do to deal with that.

00:44:57.470 --> 00:45:00.490
And there's more mobile
software kinds of things.

00:45:00.490 --> 00:45:04.350
But for Facebook to spend $22
billion dollars for WhatsApp,

00:45:04.350 --> 00:45:09.924
I mean, that tells you they
see some vision of advertising

00:45:09.924 --> 00:45:16.336
in messaging, or else
they're just stupid.

00:45:16.336 --> 00:45:17.947
I don't know.

00:45:17.947 --> 00:45:19.030
MALE SPEAKER: Anyone else?

00:45:19.030 --> 00:45:21.070
I have another one
if no one-- OK.

00:45:21.070 --> 00:45:23.700
Larry, you talk to,
obviously, senior executives

00:45:23.700 --> 00:45:26.955
at a wide variety of
companies and company types.

00:45:26.955 --> 00:45:29.030
What do you hear about Google?

00:45:29.030 --> 00:45:33.890
What do senior executives
say about Google

00:45:33.890 --> 00:45:36.490
from a macro
perspective if they do,

00:45:36.490 --> 00:45:39.840
and what do they think their
relationship with Google

00:45:39.840 --> 00:45:41.030
should be?

00:45:41.030 --> 00:45:43.320
LARRY WEBER: I think if they
understand Google at all,

00:45:43.320 --> 00:45:46.605
there's very much from
a search point of view

00:45:46.605 --> 00:45:48.025
and a page search point of view.

00:45:48.025 --> 00:45:53.490
They realize there's sort
of a real basic elder

00:45:53.490 --> 00:45:56.840
or a mythic value to Google.

00:45:56.840 --> 00:45:59.510
So obviously, you've
won the search.

00:45:59.510 --> 00:46:02.660
At least searches that
exists today, you've won that

00:46:02.660 --> 00:46:04.470
and we need to
spend money in that.

00:46:04.470 --> 00:46:08.740
Because if I make hot,
red convertibles at Ford

00:46:08.740 --> 00:46:10.240
and I'm in charge
of marketing that,

00:46:10.240 --> 00:46:15.950
I better own sexy,
hot, red convertible.

00:46:15.950 --> 00:46:18.390
The best price for
that kind of thing.

00:46:18.390 --> 00:46:19.820
I think they get that.

00:46:19.820 --> 00:46:21.570
I think some of the
things they don't get

00:46:21.570 --> 00:46:23.840
is why is Google
trying everything?

00:46:23.840 --> 00:46:25.220
Like why, you know?

00:46:25.220 --> 00:46:27.030
What is really this
Internet of Things?

00:46:27.030 --> 00:46:28.799
And why do they want
a driverless car?

00:46:28.799 --> 00:46:30.590
And why are they in
looking at health care?

00:46:30.590 --> 00:46:31.881
And what are the glasses about?

00:46:34.240 --> 00:46:38.700
How is this going to impact me,
my brand, and what we're doing?

00:46:38.700 --> 00:46:42.220
And I think to
remain an innovator,

00:46:42.220 --> 00:46:44.090
you have to do that stuff.

00:46:44.090 --> 00:46:45.800
But I think the
clarity of how you're

00:46:45.800 --> 00:46:50.176
going to help big brands
I think can be better.

00:46:50.176 --> 00:46:54.220
I think right now, it's more
on that paid search level

00:46:54.220 --> 00:46:58.070
and more in the era when
most people wake up and go

00:46:58.070 --> 00:47:01.860
to your landing page before
anything else and something.

00:47:01.860 --> 00:47:05.470
How does that help me
at IBM, or how does it

00:47:05.470 --> 00:47:09.430
help me at John Deere.

00:47:09.430 --> 00:47:13.720
And I think that needs to
more corporate understanding

00:47:13.720 --> 00:47:17.637
of brand versus just
the tactical work.

00:47:17.637 --> 00:47:18.970
But I think they respect Google.

00:47:18.970 --> 00:47:22.180
I think the smarter
conversations

00:47:22.180 --> 00:47:28.260
I have, like, who do you think
the two or three people that

00:47:28.260 --> 00:47:30.860
might win this
sort of everything

00:47:30.860 --> 00:47:37.070
from Internet of Things to
the next wave of computing,

00:47:37.070 --> 00:47:39.680
mobility, and all that.

00:47:39.680 --> 00:47:42.110
And I constantly say
it's the two biggest sumo

00:47:42.110 --> 00:47:46.490
wrestlers in my opinion
are Amazon and Google.

00:47:46.490 --> 00:47:52.095
The last time I saw Bezos
being interviewed out

00:47:52.095 --> 00:47:58.240
at one of those highfalutin
Techonomy kind of things.

00:47:58.240 --> 00:48:00.950
The interviewer
said, how does it

00:48:00.950 --> 00:48:04.680
feel to be one of the greatest
retailers of all time?

00:48:04.680 --> 00:48:08.050
And he looked
physically disturbed.

00:48:08.050 --> 00:48:12.880
And he wears this baseball
hat now really low.

00:48:12.880 --> 00:48:17.180
And he goes, I am
not a retailer.

00:48:17.180 --> 00:48:20.590
And the interviewer went,
OK, but what are you?

00:48:20.590 --> 00:48:23.890
He goes, I'm the biggest
sucker of data on the planet.

00:48:23.890 --> 00:48:25.680
That's what he said.

00:48:25.680 --> 00:48:29.680
And so to show more, I think,
the positioning of Google,

00:48:29.680 --> 00:48:32.720
how you are the next
generation of data collection

00:48:32.720 --> 00:48:35.340
and how you use that to
create better brands,

00:48:35.340 --> 00:48:38.570
I think it is an important
juncture right now.

00:48:38.570 --> 00:48:42.346
By the way, I don't think
Apple's in that race

00:48:42.346 --> 00:48:43.220
or that conversation.

00:48:43.220 --> 00:48:45.820
I think Facebook
is questionable.

00:48:45.820 --> 00:48:48.240
And maybe there's a new company.

00:48:48.240 --> 00:48:51.420
There's always a new company,
but it's not Dropbox or Box.

00:48:56.740 --> 00:48:59.530
Twitter should have been
more video and visual.

00:48:59.530 --> 00:49:01.740
So there's probably
a startup that's

00:49:01.740 --> 00:49:05.220
trying to play with
co-creation of visuals

00:49:05.220 --> 00:49:08.680
or real-time sharing.

00:49:08.680 --> 00:49:09.860
Snapchat is interesting.

00:49:09.860 --> 00:49:10.800
It's getting into ads.

00:49:10.800 --> 00:49:17.410
And Instagram still is
growing quite a bit,

00:49:17.410 --> 00:49:19.890
so it seems to be
a bit of a model.

00:49:19.890 --> 00:49:23.180
But again, I don't see the
impact that a Google has had.

00:49:26.620 --> 00:49:30.070
The couple times I've
met your founders early

00:49:30.070 --> 00:49:35.390
in their careers, just
refreshing young men

00:49:35.390 --> 00:49:39.800
at the time, really, just
trying to figure out how they

00:49:39.800 --> 00:49:42.470
could move the world ahead.

00:49:42.470 --> 00:49:44.860
And I think they really
meant that they wanted Google

00:49:44.860 --> 00:49:46.592
to be a really good company.

00:49:46.592 --> 00:49:49.050
And I don't think people get
that sense as much that you've

00:49:49.050 --> 00:49:50.090
gotten so big.

00:49:50.090 --> 00:49:52.375
What do you do that's good?

00:49:52.375 --> 00:49:57.300
What do you do as a good company
for the planet, for people?

00:49:57.300 --> 00:49:59.952
MALE SPEAKER: I think that's
a good place to stop, then.

00:49:59.952 --> 00:50:00.660
Thank you, Larry.

00:50:00.660 --> 00:50:02.060
Thanks very much for joining us.

00:50:02.060 --> 00:50:02.810
LARRY WEBER: Yeah.

00:50:02.810 --> 00:50:03.910
Thanks.

